Issues.Body:
The HTTP/2 frame writer uses `lock` to ensure only one stream can write the connection at a time. For example, [Http2FrameWriter.WriteDataAsync](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/85a6cb07ae2e1adf5a03740f8d40333b7b8e360c/src/Servers/Kestrel/Core/src/Internal/Http2/Http2FrameWriter.cs#L265).

When a connection has many streams with frequent writes, there is a lot of contention on the lock. Profiling shows high CPU usage from threads fighting over the lock.

A potential improvement would be to change the writer to use a producer/consumer queue using `Channel<T>`. The streams add write operations to the queue and a single consumer loop is responsible for writing frames to the connection.

Today:

```csharp
public ValueTask<FlushResult> WriteDataAsync(byte[] data)
{
    lock (_writeLock)
    {
        _writer.Write(data);
        return _writer.FlushAsync()
    }
}
```

Future:

```csharp
public ValueTask WriteDataAsync(byte[] data)
{
    var operation = SetupWriteData(data);
    _channelWriter.TryWrite(operation);
    return operation.WaitForCompletedAsync();
}

// Consumer loop that reads operations from channel
private async ValueTask WriterConsumer()
{
    while (true)
    {
        if (!await _channelReader.WaitToReadAsync())
        {
            return;
        }

        if (_channelReader.TryRead(out T item))
        {
            switch (item.OperationType)
            {
                case OperationType.WriteData:
                    _writer.Write(item.Data);
                    await _writer.FlushAsync();
                    item.Complete();
                    break;
                case OperationType.WriteHeaders:
                    // etc..
                    break;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Summary

It seems the Razor engine is built with extensions (features/passes) in mind, but most of it seems to be internal.

I and many others (people that want minification in Razor, like this [one](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/23570)) would like to manipulate with the Razor syntax tree, and the best way seems to be to hook in a pass to in the Razor engine, as it already parses the Razor code and reuse the syntax tree for many passes.

However, the list of passes can't be modified without significant changes. Since the DefaultRazorProjectEngineBuilder is not provided by dependency injection, nor is the instance reachable through a delegate or similar.

This means in order for me to inject a pass, I have to resort to replacing the RazorProjectEngine, which is not optimal:

```csharp
services.Replace(ServiceDescriptor.Singleton<RazorProjectEngine>(x =>
{
    RazorProjectFileSystem fileSystem = x.GetRequiredService<RazorProjectFileSystem>();
    RazorProjectEngine projectEngine = RazorProjectEngine.Create(RazorConfiguration.Default, fileSystem, builder =>
    {
        builder.Phases.Add(new AwesomeFeature());
    });

    return projectEngine;
}));
```

The second problem comes when you then try and inherit from [IRazorSyntaxTreePass](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/main/src/Razor/Microsoft.AspNetCore.Razor.Language/src/IRazorSyntaxTreePass.cs), but you can't since it is internal. It even has a note that says "Internal until we flesh out public RazorSyntaxTree API". Until it is public, it is impossible to modify the syntax tree.

Razor has an extensible design, but it seems to be completely closed off users. I can't seem to find an issue that tracks this design change, so I created one.

Can we open up the APIs a little bit? Change a couple of internal interfaces/classes to be public?

* Assume some mechanism exists that notifies the framework when a delta is applied.
* We introduce a new contract that is implemented by `ComponentBase`. This allows components to subscribe to events that make them aware that a rendering is being triggered as a response to delta apply event:

```C#
IHotReloadableComponent
{
    void UseHotReloadableContext(HotReloadableContext context);
}

class HotReloadableContext
{
